ndra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Marmande I was born in 1160, in Marmande, Lot-et-Garonne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, his father, Bouchard Ier de Marmande, was 35 and his mother, Louise de Bergerac, was 25. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Agathe de Montsoreau. He died after 1224."},"et":{"1160–après 1224":"1160–pärast 1224","1160–1224":"1160–1224","1170–1210":"1170–1210","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1195–1256":"1195–1256","1125–1186":"1125–1186","1135–1197":"1135–1197","1186":"1186","1197":"1197","1185":"1185","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","ABT 1195":"umbes 1195","après 1224":"pärast 1224","1125":"1125","1224":"1224","1135":"1135","1256":"1256","1210":"1210","Vellèches,862